<br>
<br>
Many parents hope that their chil'uns learn these select and valuable skills in Elementary School.  I myself learned the basics of human communication first at Byron Elementary in Byron, IL, then at Palisades Elementary, in Lake Oswego, Oregon.<br>
<br>
While some people may not gain these skills in their early days, or even in their late days, they are not necessary to survive.  But, these skills are necessary to survive in a communicative world, one, like which we live in, and more importantly, the world (alot of us spend more time in) we love (ie. Everquest).<br>
<br>
I have been reading these previous posts and have come up with a conclusion.  Throughout the ages of Drinal, many guilds have come and gone.  Councils like UGoD have attempted to standardize and legislate the masses, directing times and dates, but, alas, it too failed over time, perhaps from laziness or from disuse, who can say.<br>
<br>
As guilds move up into, or out of an area like NToV, of course the right to kill, the right to loot, and the right to exist in such an esteemed area come into question.<br>
<br>
We saw Cats arrive and succeed through months of effort. We saw Vice, a collection of pimpness stand and fight for the right to exist and for a while they did.  Though, as Tekai said, leadership came into question and people flamed Vice until they broke up.<br>
<br>
Peer pressure among guilds is huge.  Imagine no one liking you.  In a perfect world people would be immune to such nonsense, a collection of stupidity and lack of maturity.  But, people have feelings, and it was sad to see such a guild leave.<br>
<br>
Yes, we saw FeMax,CT/WL, and TK also take the next step, and they too, for the most part have gone.  The next wave began a bit ago with the domination of Ntov by GoTK, Unc, DM, and ofcourse, the topic of this flame, UrC, or as I like to call them, CR (not for corpse retrival, oh no, but for chaos unrivaled, which i think sounds better and doesnt clash with Unc).  You may say Avatar took up the flame from Vice, and could have listed AA as a possibility at one time yet both guilds suffered from loss of members and once again, leadership problems.<br>
<br>
I do not think it necessary to flame any guild for taking the next logical step.  While Seke and Kronill and a few others above speak of etiquette, you must take into play the actions taken by both DM and CR (UrC once again).<br>
<br>
DM took aary, a considerable mob to those guilds not used to Ntov as many of you know.  I was once asked to join DM, cause Kronill's a good guy, yet from timezone difficulties and dedication to a guild that I helped start then kicked me for insane reasons (then later became Avatar), i politely said no.  I still like Kronill, though i have not been playing recently due to health issues and constant hospital stays<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Back to the point.  After taking Aary, it is my understanding that DM left because no further mobs were up, understandable.  Then, later, with &quot;no sufficient forces&quot; availible, they took gimp Dain, while CR took a few mobs from NToV.<br>
<br>
This is what i understand from this:  some of the mobs in NToV are easily doable with &quot;A LOT&quot; less people now with new abilities and hp/levels, yet DM took Dain.  I do not question DM and I understand their point of view, whether the decision made was a good one or not.<br>
<br>
Yet, on the other hand I also understand CR's standpoint in saying that, while they took Aary, how long must the rest of the server wait before it becomes free game.<br>
<br>
Now, if I was a raid leader/officer of CR, i would /who all &quot;blah blah&quot; and see the situation of certain guilds, the new wave per se, to see their status at that time.  Had i known of DMs kill earlier, however many days/hours ago that was, i would have told DM of my action and yes, then discussed the situation.  If, at that time, they think they want to leave/finish Dain then arrive and do NToV, whether they had enough people or not is up to them, and if they failed, its free game.<br>
<br>
I hope my standpoint makes some sense, and the rest of the message is taken, if possible, to some understanding.<br>
